07455nam a22014055i 9780691227740DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20221998nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2020759468  a9780691227740  a(DE-B1597)576642  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aF158.44 4aPN2285b.R543 1998 7aHIS0360402bisacsh04a790.209222231 aRigal, Laura, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe American Manufactory :bArt, Labor, and the World of Things in the Early Republic /cLaura Rigal. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2022] 4c©1998  a1 online resource (272 p.) :b14 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tILLUSTRATIONS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tINTRODUCTION. The Extended Republic in the Age of Manufactures -- tPART I: FEDERAL MECHANICS -- tCHAPTER ONE. Raising the Roof: Authors, Architects, and Artisans in the Grand Federal Procession of 1788 -- tCHAPTER TWO. The Mechanic as the Author of His Life: John Fitch's “Life” and “Steamboat History” -- tPART II: THE MAMMOTH STATE -- tCHAPTER THREE. Peale's Mammoth -- tCHAPTER FOUR. The American Lounger: Figures of Failure and Fatigue in the Port Folio, 1801–1809 -- tPART III: THE STRONG BOX -- tCHAPTER FIVE. Feathered Federalism: Alexander Wilson's American Ornithology, 1807-181 -- tCHAPTER SIX. Picture-Nation: Pat Lyon at the Forge, 1798-1829 -- tNOTES -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis cultural history of American federalism argues that nation-building cannot be understood apart from the process of industrialization and the making of the working class in the late-eighteenth-century United States. Citing the coincidental rise of federalism and industrialism, Laura Rigal examines the creations and performances of writers, collectors, engineers, inventors, and illustrators who assembled an early national "world of things," at a time when American craftsmen were transformed into wage laborers and production was rationalized, mechanized, and put to new ideological purposes. American federalism emerges here as a culture of self-making, in forms as various as street parades, magazine writing, painting, autobiography, advertisement, natural history collections, and trials and trial transcripts. Chapters center on the craftsmen who celebrated the Constitution by marching in Philadelphia's Grand Federal Procession of 1788; the autobiographical writings of John Fitch, an inventor of the steamboat before Fulton; the exhumation and museum display of the "first American mastodon" by the Peale family of Philadelphia; Joseph Dennie's literary miscellany, the Port Folio; the nine-volume American Ornithology of Alexander Wilson; and finally the autobiography and portrait of Philadelphia locksmith Pat Lyon, who was falsely imprisoned for bank robbery in 1798 but eventually emerged as an icon for the American working man. Rigal demonstrates that federalism is not merely a political movement, or an artifact of language, but a phenomenon of culture: one among many innovations elaborated in the "manufactory" of early American nation-building.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aArt and societyzUnited StatesxHistoryy18th century. 0aArt and societyzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aArt, AmericanxSocial aspectszPennsylvaniay18th centuryxthemes, motives, etc. 0aArt, AmericanzPennsylvaniazPhiladelphiay18th centuryxThemes, motives. 0aArt, AmericanzPennsylvaniazPhiladelphiay19th centuryxThemes, motives. 0aArtisanszPennsylvaniazPhiladelphiaxHistoryy18th century. 0aArtisanszPennsylvaniazPhiladelphiaxHistoryy19th century. 0aEnlightenmentzUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aEnlightenm